Unsupervised Learning¶

The key distinction between the two is:

  • Supervised Learning has BOTH Input and Output information
  • Unsupervised Learning ONLY has Input information

Most Unsupervised algorithms come down to some form of Clustering

Clustering is the task of grouping a set of objects in such a way that objects in the same group are more similar to each other than to those in other groups. -Wikipedia

There are SEVERAL different strategies for identifying clusters in a dataset, but the most commonly used is K-Means Clustering.

K-Means Clustering Algorithm¶

Before starting, pick $K$. This will be the number of groups identified.

  1. Randomly select the $K$ group centers.
  2. Find the distance from the group centers to all points in data set.
    • Identify each data point as "belonging" to the group that is the closest
  3. Update the group centers to be the average of all the points in the group
  4. Repeat step 2 and 3 until the group centers stop changing

Hierarchical Clustering¶

The other dominant strategy for finding groups in a data set.

Hierarchical clustering is a method of cluster analysis which seeks to build a hierarchy of clusters. -Wikipedia

There are two main varieties: top down and bottom up. They differ in whether you start with individual groups or a single group, then split. Either way, the individual distance between data points is used to create the groups.

The result of every hierarchical cluster algorithm is a Dendogram, a visual image that shows how groups are formed. This picture gives us the complete grouping available.

Advantages of hierarchical clustering include:

  • The ability to use ANY distance metric
  • All possible groups are found

Some of the disadvantages include:

  • Greater computational cost
  • Difficult to know what "level" of clustering is correct
  • Sensitive to the distance metric used
